    • Method Detail

      • allowSystemExit0

        public void allowSystemExit0()

      • testCountNumbers

        public void testCountNumbers()
        Tests the countNumbers(x) method. Asserts that:
        • countNumbers(x) counts the occurrence of numbers in the tuple
        • countNumbers(x) returns 0 for a x that is not in the tuple
        • countNumbers(x) returns 0 if x is lower than 1
        • countNumbers(x) is consistent over two calls

      • testEquals

        public void testEquals()
        Tests the equals(x) method. Asserts that:
        • equals(x) returns true if x is a LinkedNaturalNumberTuple that was instantiated with the same array as this.
        • equals(x) returns false if x is a LinkedNaturalNumberTuple that has different numbers in it than this.
        • equals(x) returns false if x is a LinkedNaturalNumberTuple that has the same numbers in a different order as this in it.
        • equals(new Object()) returns false
        • equals(this) returns true
        • equals(x) is consistent over two calls

      • testIndexOf

        public void testIndexOf()
        Tests the indexOf(x) method. Asserts that:
        • indexOf(x) returns the first occurrence of x, where 0 is the first element in the tuple.
        • indexOf(x) returns -1,if x is not in the tuple.
        • indexOf(x) returns -1 if x is smaller than 1.
        • indexOf(x) is consitent over two calls

      • testInsert

        public void testInsert()
        Tests the insert(x) method. Asserts that:
        • insert(x) does not insert x if x is smaller than 1.
        • insert(x) does not insert x at the end of the tuple otherwise.
        • insert(x) does the above on an empty tuple, too.

      • testMax

        public void testMax()
        Tests the max() method. Asserts that:
        • max() returns the greatest number in the tuple.
        • max() returns -1 if the tuple is empty.

      • testMin

        public void testMin()
        Tests the min() method. Asserts that:
        • min() returns the smallest number in the tuple.
        • min() returns -1 if the tuple is empty.

      • testConstructor

        public void testConstructor()
        Tests the constructor. Asserts that:
        • The constructor runs without an Exception if called with an Array of Integers
        • The constructor runs without an Exception if called with null

      • testRemove

        public void testRemove()
        Tests the remove(x) method. Asserts that:
        • remove(x) removes all occurrences of x in the tuple and returns true if x was in the tuple
        • remove(x) returns false if x was not in the tuple
        • remove(x) returns false if called a second time with the same parameter x

      • testPackage

        public void testPackage()
        Tests the package name of the implemented class. Asserts that:
        • The package name starts with edu.kit.informatik

      • testClassName

        public void testClassName()
        Tests the class name of the implemented class. Asserts that:
        • The class name is LinkedNaturalNumberTuple

      • testToString

        public void testToString()
        Tests the toString() method. Asserts that:
        • toString() returns a String of numbers of the tuple, separated by commas, that does not contain any whitespace.
        • toString() returns "" (empty String) if called on a empty tuple.

      • testSwap

        public void testSwap()
        Tests the swap(x, y) method. swap(x, y) is called on a tuple that has the number a at position x and the number b at position y. This method asserts that:
        • swap(x, y) returns true and after the call the number at position x is b and the number at position y is a, while other numbers have been left unchanged.
        • the above happens regardless if x<y, x>y or x=y, as a long as x and y are valid indexes in the tuple.
        • swap(x, y) returns true if called a second time and after the call the number at position x is a and the number at position y is b, while other numbers have been left unchanged.
        • the above happens regardless if x<y, x>y or x=y, as a long as x and y are valid indexes in the tuple.
        • swap(x, y) returns false and leaves the tuple unchanged if either x or y isn't a valid index in the tuple.
        • the above happens regardless if x<y, x>y or x=y.
